article.description:
The top shot-blocker in the WNBA the last six years, 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek had a team-record nine against San Antonio Saturday
to help lead the Connecticut Sun to an 80-69 win over the Silver
Spurs.
article.headline: On offense, Connecticut hits seven 3s in victory
article.linkText: Dydek has Sun-record 9 blocks in win over Stars
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Still adjusting to her new role with
her new team, Margo Dydek relied on what she does best -- block
shots.

The top shot-blocker in the WNBA the last six years, the
7-foot-2 Dydek had a team-record nine against San Antonio Saturday
to help lead the Connecticut Sun to an 80-69 win over the Silver
Stars.

Connecticut acquired her in a draft-day trade, sending
first-round pick Katie Feenstra, a 6-8 center out of Liberty, to
San Antonio. Dydek was the last player in camp and didn't join the
Sun until after their first two exhibition game because she was
still playing in Europe.

"I still need some time to get in the rhythm to know my new
teammates. I feel better than last week even," Dydek said. "The
blocked shots is what I like to do."

The nine blocked shots were one shy of her career high.

Dydek's rejections helped get Connecticut out in transition,
especially in the second half. The Sun even scored on her jump
ball. Towering over 5-9 Marie Ferdinand late in the second half on
a jump ball, Dydek easily flicked the ball to Katie Douglas out in
front on a dead run. The result was an easy layup.

"We got her for her defense," Taj McWilliams-Franklin said of
Dydek. "She altered many more shots than she blocked, which helped
us hold them under 50 percent."

The Silver Stars shot 43 percent from the floor, hitting 27 of
63.

Dydek, Douglas and McWilliams-Franklin all finished with 15
points for Connecticut. McWilliams-Franklin, who played limited
minutes because of a sore knee, had eight of her points in the
first 3 minutes of the game.

Douglas came up big in the second half with consecutive
3-pointers to help the Sun pull away down the stretch. She and
Lindsay Whalen each had six of the Sun's 25 assists on 34 field
goals. The 25 assists were one short of a Sun record.

"We definitely executed. That's what you want," Sun guard
Lindsay Whalen said.

Wendy Palmer-Daniel, a former member of the Sun, had 14 points
and a team-high 13 rebounds for San Antonio. LaToya Thomas led the
Silver Stars with 17 points and Feenstra finished with 13 off the
bench.

"We had a hard time stopping them," Silver Stars coach Dan
Hughes said. "Defensively we never got into a good rhythm."

The Silver Stars were coming off their only win of the season
after opening with five straight losses, and the rookie center
scored 16 points in the victory. Feenstra provided another spark
Saturday midway through the first half as she and Dydek dueled in
the post.

In a matchup of two of the tallest players in the league,
Feenstra banked her first shot over Dydek to draw San Antonio even
at 8-all and she would go on to score nine points in the period.
She also drew a pair of fouls from Dydek. Feenstra's back-to-back
buckets with 4:33 left gave San Antonio its biggest lead of the
half at 29-23.

But reserve forward Brooke Wyckoff hit a 3-pointer with 3:01 to
tie it at 29-all. She also made a key steal in the final possession
of the half and found a streaking Nykesha Sales for a layup as time
ran out to give Connecticut a 37-34 lead at the break.

"That helped us," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "Brooke got a
tip, (Nykesha) got a basket. I thought it energized us. The
momentum had changed with about two minutes left."

Douglas had 11 points in the second half, including nine in a
13-6 run to give the Sun some breathing room. Connecticut led by as
many as 16 in the period.

Dydek, a longtime member of the Polish national team, played the
last two years with San Antonio and Saturday was her first meeting
against her old teammates.

"I'm used to playing in Europe with so many different teams.
I'm used to playing against my ex-teammates," she said. "It is a
bit strange, but that's the game. We just play the game."

Her performance drew praise from some of her former teammates.

"She played a very good game," Silver Stars guard Shannon
Johnson said. "But I would have liked it more if she was still
playing for our team."
